      "content": "hey i was looking at my student loan statement and the principal isnt going down as much as i thought it would even though i pay the same amount every month. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated on a declining balance?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the student loan statement, a treasure trove of numbers and percentages, much like a goblin's hoard of shiny trinkets. Now, when you pay off your student loan, the principal—the original amount borrowed—is like a mountain of gold that goblins guard jealously. As you chip away at the mountain with your monthly payments, the interest, that pesky goblin, only cares about the remaining gold, not the gold you've already taken. So, as you pay down the principal, the interest goblins get a smaller piece of the pie, but they still get their share. It's like goblins sharing a pie; the bigger the pie, the more goblins get, but as the pie shrinks, each goblin gets a smaller slice. Keep chipping away at that mountain, and soon you'll see the goblins' share diminish, and you'll be closer to reclaiming your treasure.",
